ABSTRACT

Writing in a logical sense is the representation of speech. The variation in people’s handwriting has an effect on the productivity of employees in different sectors such as banks, postal services, schools amongst others. Researchers have continuously worked on developing intelligent systems that can recognize handwriting of different authors. This research work presents a comparative analysis of three different machine learning classification algorithms (SVM, KNN, and RFC models) for hand writing recognition. The model performance was evaluated using accuracy score, recall score, precision score, balanced accuracy score, f1 score, and recognition time. The comparative analysis was done on the NIST database 19. After training and evaluating the machine learning models on the same dataset, the RFC model performs better on the test data with a 100% accuracy score, 100 % recall score, 100% precision score, 100% balanced accuracy score, 100% F1 score, and recognition time of 25.47milliseconds (ms) followed by the SVM with an accuracy score of 97.82%, 97.82% recall score, 97.88% precision score, 97.82% balanced accuracy score, 97.84% F1 score, and recognition time of 72.13 milliseconds (ms), and the KNN classification performs worse with an accuracy score of 67.95%, 67.95% recall score, 70.58% precision score, 67.95% balanced accuracy score, 67.93% F1 score, and recognition time of 32.54 milliseconds (ms) after hyperparameter tuning of the models. The handwriting recognition system was designed by deploying the RFC model as a web-based application using Flask python web framework.

CHAPTER ONE

INTRODUCTION

1.1 Background of the study

Writing, in a logical sense, is the representation of speech. To recount the history of writing, even in its most basic meaning, it seems necessary to start with a broader definition of writing as the creation of visual marks or other artefacts for communication and expression (Olson, 2009).

However, the famous cave drawings dating back 40,000 years have been discovered at Lascaux and Altamira etched on a skeleton, are all included. the day gods expression, in China, dating back some 10,000 years, in this more inclusive notion of writing as visual communications, as they are conventional signs that are intended to represent and convey information (Olson, 2009).

Before 3,000 BCE, the Sumerians in ancient Mesopotamia were the first to establish writing. Prior to 600 BCE, it was invented in Mesoamerica, and before the year 1300 BCE, it was presumably invented in China. It could have happened independently in Egypt circa 3,000 BCE, yet given Egypt's geographical closeness to Mesopotamia, the Egyptians may have learned from the Sumerians (Forrester & Forrester, 2016).

Writing systems are divided into three categories (Forrester & Forrester, 2016). The writing systems might represent the entire word, a single syllable, or a single sound. The system is referred to as logographic because it employs logograms, which are written symbols that represent certain concepts. As a modern Japanese and Chinese writing system, the first Sumerian California, Egyptian hieroglyphics, and Mayan glyphs are all logographic writing systems. Syllabic is a system in which the written sign represents a syllable. In the ancient world, syllabic writing systems were more common than they are today. The alphabetical writing system is the most widely used nowadays (Forrester & Forrester, 2016). It is impossible to ignore alphabets and their influence on the development of western civilization (Schement et al., 2002). Because phonemes (differentiable units of speech within a language) may be represented by alphabets, alphabetic texts are often similar to spoken language. This makes learning, reading, and writing pretty simple. It also facilitates computing and printing. Other writing systems, such as logographic and syllabic systems, on the other hand, are more difficult to learn and comprehend. The alphabet is the logical culmination of an ever-increasing amount of abstraction (Forrester & Forrester, 2016). The alphabet is universally applicable and widely acknowledged as the teleological objective of the history of writing.

However, the importance of writing cannot be overemphasized as writing effectively is a skill that is based on the cognitive domain (Defazio et al., 2010). It entails the new information is acquired, comprehended, applied, and synthesized. Success in writing, in the eyes of a professor, includes more than just adhering to the rules of writing also entails creative inspiration, problem-solving, contemplation, and rewriting, all of which culminate in a finished work (Forrester & Forrester, 2016). Writing, From the standpoint of a student, it may be a time-consuming and even dreaded process of attempting to put thoughts on paper while understanding writing conventions such as spelling, citations, and syntax.

Furthermore, it is uncertain if states as a form of government could have survived if writing or a similar record-keeping system like Inca qui (that is, a quipu from the Inca Empire that is currently on display at the Larco Museum) had not been established. It would be difficult or impossible to manage or control any political institution larger than a chiefdom if writing did not exist. As civilizations grew larger, a writing or comparable record-keeping system was required to regulate the administration of the society's government. However, we want to investigate this writing to develop a system that will assist in identifying this alphabetic writing system, which is the most widely used (Forrester & Forrester, 2016).

Object identification, defined as the process of identifying an object based on training examples, is a fundamental topic in the automation sector that has sparked a lot of interest from academic and industry organizations. This is similar to the way human beings can detect and identify the object when they view the object (H. Liu et al., 2016). The researcher, therefore, proposes a system that employs a machine-learning classification technique for handwriting recognition, which is employed in a variety of industries such as schools, banks, postal services, and so on. The machine learning algorithm selected for comparison and classification is support vector machine (SVM), k-nearest neighbors (KNN), and random forest classifier (RFC). Handwriting recognition will be implemented using the best of the three classification machine learning estimators chosen. As a result, based on Artificial Neural Networks (ANN), this work gives a model for handwriting recognition.

1.2 Motivation of the study

OCR (Optical Character Recognition) is a piece of software that turns scanned documents into editable text searchable files. A growing number of papers need to be scanned in today's society so that they may be easily read and shared via electronic methods. A scan, on the other hand, is simply a picture capture of the original document that cannot be altered or searched through. Employees must now manually correct or search through several pages, resulting in a decrease in inefficiency.

This difficulty is solved by OCR, which makes text documents searchable (Sarvaramini et al., 2018). For this work, the researcher will be developing an OCR system by carrying out a comparative analysis on three machine learning algorithms; SVM, KNN, and RFC, to determine the algorithm with the highest accuracy, balanced accuracy, precision, f1, recall, and cross-validation score. The most efficient algorithm which has the best classification metrics is used to implement the handwriting recognition system.

1.3 Statement of the Problem

There have been a good number of machine learning algorithms that have been developed proved to be efficient and carry out the assignment of handwriting recognition. These algorithms have their advantages and disadvantages as well as their preferred use cases. However, there is yet to be a definitive study to find out which of them is the most efficient and which performs best given specific classification metrics. A study is needed to contrast these algorithmic implementations to know which is the most efficient.

The results from the model evaluation will determine which machine learning model will be used to deploy the handwriting text recognition system.

1.4 Aim and objectives of the study

The work aims to carry out a comparative analysis of SVM, KNN, and RFC machine learning classification models for handwriting recognition.

To achieve the above aim, the objectives of the study shall be:

  1. To pre-process the dataset for all algorithms.
  2. To build the machine learning classification models.
  3. To compare the performance of the models in (ii) using accuracy, balanced accuracy score, f1 score, precision score, recall score, recognition time, and cross-validation score.
  4. To deploy the best-performing model (iii) into a web-based application.

1.5 Research Questions

The study tends to find answers to questions as follows:

  1. Can computer systems be used to detect handwriting?
  2. How does a computer detect and recognize characters?
  3. Can artificial intelligence be used by postal services, banks to gain a clearer view of handwriting and signatures?
  4. How does AI improve the accuracy of recognizing handwritten characters?
  5. Why compare machine learning algorithms for handwriting recognition?

1.6 Scope and limitation of the study

This research explains the application of machine learning for handwriting recognition and comparison among some algorithms which can be used to implement the handwritten text recognition system. This study focuses on scanning text on paper using a phone camera, the image is sent to the system and the system converts the image containing texts into a machine-readable format.

The limitations of this research work include:

The research is centred on the recognition of English alphabets (A-Z) (a-z) and digits (0-9) for handwriting recognition.

  1. Due to time and financial constraints implementing the model into deployable software will not be possible.
  2. Only one character will be recognized at a time, that is, the system will segment the handwritten texts and recognized each character in real-time before converting and displaying the entire complete texts in a machine-readable format.
  3. Handwriting is subject to a high conflict in writing style between authors. Factors contain the size, rotation, lightening, and tilt or the equivalence of dissimilar focus.

1.7 Significance of the study

This research is very important as there has been a constant text document on paper. The number of bank checks, mailing documents, signature continue to grow from year to year. There is a need for machines to be developed or modelled which can be able to carry out such tasks as identifying text on paper. And in this research, the researcher seeks to check for the best algorithm that will give an optimal solution to the problem. The study has wide areas of application ranging from banks, postal services, and schools.

2.1 Introduction

Artificial intelligence (AI) is a general term that refers to the use of a computer to simulate intelligent behaviour with little or no human involvement by training and extracting features from data (Hamet & Tremblay, 2017).

The intelligence of humans makes them different from computers (Obaid et al., 2016). Humans can perform a variety of jobs that machines cannot perform on their own. Handwritten text recognition is one of these jobs. Artificial intelligence provides a real-time solution to vast and difficult computer challenges.

Optical character recognition (OCR) is an automatic identification technology that can be used to automate a variety of tasks (Karthick et al., 2019). Optical character recognition is frequently utilized in a variety of critical applications (Bari et al., 2019). In addition to optical character recognition, HDR (handwritten digit recognition) is employed (OCR). Checks are deposited in banks via the internet. The amount on the checks is automatically detected by HDR without the need for Human action. Recognition of handwritten characters (HCR) is a type of optical character recognition that translates text into machine-readable formats. The effectiveness of HCR is determined by the classifiers employed and the retrieved feature (Surya Nath R S & Afseena, 2015).

However, handwriting has become an important component of our day-to-day lives (Yousaf et al., 2018). Signature verification, author identification, and handwritten text recognition (HTR) are only a few of the patterns that handwriting absorbs. The majority of study in these areas is based on handwritten text recognition since it covers a diverse application like processing of historic documents and processing of automatic postal. Handwritten characters are simple to recognize and identify for humans. However, due to the high variations of different handwriting styles, it becomes difficult for machines. As a result, handwritten text recognition performance is determined by the initial dataset used in training (Yousaf et al., 2018).

This research is based on artificial intelligence for comparing the machine learning algorithm with the highest accuracy score, recall score, f1 score, precision score, balanced accuracy score, and cross-validation score between SVM, KNN, and random forest classifier for offline character recognition by checking performance based on accuracy score, precision score, recall score, f1 score, balanced accuracy score, and cross-validation score.

2.2 Machine Learning

While working at IBM in 1959, Arthur Samuel, an American pioneer in machine learning, computer gaming, and artificial intelligence, coined the word “machine learning” Arthur described machine learning as a study area that enables computers to learn without specific programming (Dönmez, 2013).

Machine learning (ML) is an AI area that allows machines to learn without explicit programming by exposing them to sets of data and allowing them to learn a certain task via experience. using complex mathematical and statistical methods (Bazazeh & Shubair, 2017). Machine learning has enabled computers to accomplish intellectual problems that were previously handled by humans on their own. Machine learning approaches have been widely used in the construction of prediction models to aid decision-making throughout the last few decades.

Recent advancements and developments in technical disciplines and logistics have addressed science's concerns and have had a positive impact by avoiding obstacles faced by persons who are totally or partially challenged and disabled with image processing, microcontrollers, feature extraction material, and trainers’ ideas are all used to aid. The proposed proposal is feasible to implement (Kumbhar & Kunjir, 2017). Support vector machines, K-nearest neighbors, and Random forest will be compared in this research.

2.2.1 Types of Learning

Machine learning is the process of creating algorithms that allow a computer to learn. Learning is a process of detecting statistical regularities or other patterns in data, rather than a conscious activity. As a result, many machine learning algorithms will resemble how people approach a learning problem. (Abdi, 2016).

There are four different types of machine learning algorithms (Sarker, 2021). These are supervised learning, unsupervised learning, semi-supervised learning, and reinforcement learning.

2.2.1.1 Supervised Learning

The goal of supervised learning in machine learning is to use sample input-output pairs to train a function that converts input to an output. From labelled training data and a set of training examples, it infers a function (Sarker, 2021).

The most prevalent approach used for training neural networks and decision trees is supervised learning (Abdi, 2016). Both of these methods rely heavily on the data provided by the pre-determined classes. In the case of neural networks, classification is used to discover the network's error and then adapt it to reduce it; in the case of decision trees, classification is used to determine which characteristics provide the most information that can be used to solve the classification puzzle. Figure 2.1 depicts the method of applying supervised machine learning to a real-life problem. Supervised learning can be used in both classification and regression applications.

2.2.1.1.1 Decision Tree

The decision tree algorithm is a supervised learning technique that is typically used to solve classification problems. (Abdi, 2016). It works for both categorical and continuous dependent variables. This method divides the data into two or more homogeneous groups. Each node represents qualities, and each branch indicates a possible value for the node. Every tree is made up of branches and nodes in a group to be categorized. To make as many separate groups as feasible, this is done using the most important features or independent variables. Starting with the sub-data are categorised by examining the attribute defined by that node and continuing along the branch of the tree according to the value of the attribute (Sarker, 2021). The most common criteria for splitting are "gini" for Gini impurity and "entropy" information gain, which may be expressed quantitatively as seen below.

2.2.1.1.3 Support Vector Machines

The SVM was invented by Vapnik and intended to be applied to many types of recognition problems (Chumuang & Ketcham, 2018). The support vector machine (SVM), is one of the best machine learning algorithms, which was proposed in the 1990s and mostly used for pattern recognition (Pradhan, 2012). This method has been used to handle a variety of pattern classification problems, including image recognition, audio recognition, text categorization, face identification, and faulty card detection. SVM employs a data dispersion technique. An SVM model is a hyperplane representation of data examples (Kumbhar & Kunjir, 2017). As demonstrated in figure 2.3, the data examples are represented as points, and a hyperplane is a two-dimensional plane. When compared to large datasets, SVM performs exceptionally well on small and constrained datasets. The ‘Gap Trick' is a method for classifying unknown data examples in which the points are categorised by reference to the distance between the classes of the data point (Kumbhar & Kunjir, 2017).

Figure 2.3 classification by support vector machine (Kumbhar & Kunjir, 2017).

2.2.1.1.4 K-Nearest neighbors

The K-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithm is a non-generalizing “instance-based learning” or “lazy learning” technique. (Sarker, 2021). The KNN classifier's logic is simple, and it's based on supervised learning approaches that may be applied to both classification and regression issues. Because it is typically beneficial to consider more than one neighbor, the technique is more often known as KNN classification, in which the k-nearest neighbors are utilized to determine the class. The KNN classifier's logic is simple, and it's based on supervised learning approaches that may be applied to both classification and regression issues. Because it is typically beneficial to consider more than one neighbor, the technique is more often known as KNN classification, in which the k-nearest neighbors are utilized to determine the class (Singh et al., 2001).

While KNN is relatively unaffected by trained noisy data, accuracy is highly dependent on data quality. The most difficult part of k-nearest neighbor is figuring out how many neighbors to take into account. (Sarker, 2021).

2.2.1.1.5 Random Forest Classifier

Leo Breiman, who was influenced by Amit and Geman, introduced random forests (Cutler et al., 2012). The random forest, also known as random choice forests, is an ensemble learning method for regression, classification, and other problems that works by training a large number of decision trees and then producing a class that is the mode of the classes or the mean forecast of the individual trees.

This method uses “parallel ensembling” Figure 2.4 shows how to fit numerous decision tree classifiers simultaneously using the majority voting or averages for the outcome or final result, using different data set sub-samples (Sarker, 2021). Hence, the random forest minimizes overfitting and Prediction accuracy and control are improved. Consequently, the random forest classifier will perform better in prediction than the decision tree. This machine learning estimator can be used to solve the problem related to both classification and regression (random forest classifier and random forest regressor), and it works well with both categorical and continuous data.

Figure 2.4 Example of a random forest classifier (Sarker, 2021).

2.2.1.2 Unsupervised Learning

Unsupervised Learning appears to be more tasking; the goal is for the computer to learn how to accomplish something without our telling it! Unsupervised learning can be approached in two ways. (Ayodele, 2014). The first method is to teach the agent by using a reward system to signify achievement rather than giving explicit categorizations. Clustering is the second type of unsupervised learning. The purpose of this sort of learning is not to increase the utility function's value, but rather to detect patterns found in the training data. Clusters are frequently assumed to fit well with intuitive classifications.

In this type of learning, There is no outcome variable for us to predict or estimate. (Abdi, 2016). It is commonly used for generative feature extraction, discovering important trends, grouping results, and for the sake of exploratory analysis. Density estimation, feature learning, clustering, dimensionality reduction, identifying anomaly detection, and identifying association rules are some of the most typical unsupervised learning tasks (Sarker, 2021).

2.2.1.2.1 K-means clustering

K-means is a supervised technique that is used to handle clustering problems (Abdi, 2016). Its procedures follow a simple and easy method of clustering. This algorithm is an iterative algorithm that attempts to separate a dataset into predetermined clusters, with individual data points belonging to only one of these clusters. It makes every effort to make data points from different clusters as comparable as possible. It distributes data points to clusters so that the total square distance between them and the centroid of the cluster (the arithmetic mean of all the data points in that cluster) is as little as possible. Between clusters, the small variation we have, The more uniform the data points are, the more accurate the results will be (Omran et al., 2007).

2.2.1.3 Semi-Supervised Learning

Semi-supervised learning mixes labelled and unlabelled instances to produce a useful function or classifier (Ayodele, 2014). Semi-supervised learning is mostly the combination of supervised and unsupervised learning, in semi-supervised learning, a system learns from both labelled and unlabelled data in a dataset. while the latter is usually mainly labelled.

The main goal of a semi-supervised learning model is to produce a more accurate prediction model result than the model’s with only labelled data. Some applications include machine translation, fraud detection, data labelling, and text classification (Sarker, 2021).

2.2.1.4 Reinforcement Learning

The machine is instructed to use reinforcement learning to make certain decisions (Abdi, 2016). The machine is subjected to a situation where it must continually adapt to teach itself by trial and error. This system tries to learn from its mistakes by capturing as much information as possible to make appropriate business decisions. As a result, this type of learning is a branch of machine learning that is concerned with how software agents should respond in a given environment in order to maximize a commutative reward.

2.3.1 Deep Learning

Deep Learning is a subfield of machines concerned with algorithms inspired by the structure and functions of the brain called artificial neural networks (Brownlee, 2018). Deep Learning is made up of an input layer, an output layer, and multiple hidden layers in between (Katz et al., 2017). A layer is made up of many nodes that are connected by specified weights to nodes from the previous layer. Deep learning refers to a class of machine learning techniques that employ numerous extractions of features raw data. Lower layers in image processing, for example, may recognize edges, whereas higher layers may recognize human concepts such as digits, letters, or faces.

The fundamental benefit of deep learning over typical machine learning approaches is based on their performances in a variety of situations, especially when learning from enormous datasets. The Multi-layer perceptron (MLP), Convolutional neural network (CNN, or ConvNet), and Long short-term memory recurrent neural network (LSTM-RNN) are the most prevalent deep learning techniques (Sarker, 2021).

2.3.1.1 Multilayer perceptron (MLP)

A multilayer perceptron is the basic structure of deep learning, commonly known as MLP (Sarker, 2021). There are at least three layers of nodes in a multilayer perceptron (MLP): an input layer, a hidden layer, and an output layer. However, apart from the input nodes, each node is a neuron with a nonlinear activation function. Figure 2.7 depicts a typical multilayer neural network with three hidden layers.

Figure 2.7 Multilayer perceptron (Sarker, 2021)

2.3.1.2 Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN, or ConVNet)

Convolutional neural networks have gotten a lot of attention and have had a big influence in recent years, thanks to their remarkable performance in particularly difficult supervised tasks (Baldominos et al., 2018).

A convolutional neural network is an example of the deep neural network that is most typically used to analyse, visualise an image in deep learning. Because of the shared weights structure and inconsistency in translation, they are also known as shift invariant or space invariant artificial neural networks. CNNs are typically employed to solve challenging imaging problems (Shea, 2015).

CNNs are similar to ANNs since they are made of features that learn patterns within the data (Shea, 2015). Each neuron will continue to accept input and act as a scalar product followed by a non-linear function. This is the foundation for a large number of artificial neural networks. Therefore, from the input raw picture vectors to the final output of the class score, the complete network will still represent a single perceptual scoring function (the weight). All of the normal ANN tips and methods will still apply in the final layer, which will contain the loss functions associated with the classes.

Figure 2.8 Convolutional neural network (Sarker, 2021)

The only distinction between CNNs and classic ANNs is that CNNs are mostly used in the field of picture pattern detection (Shea, 2015). This enables us to encode image-specific information into the design, improving the network's suitability for image focus tasks. Traditional ANNs have a hard time dealing with the computational complexity required to compute picture data, which is one of their biggest flaws (Shea, 2015).

2.3.1.3 LSTM-RNN

The long short-term memory (LSTM) architecture is a deep learning architecture that is built on artificial recurrent neural networks (RNNs). Unlike standard feed-forward neural networks, LSTM includes feedback links. When the data is in a sequential pattern, such as time or a sentence, LSTM can be utilized in time series analysis, natural language processing, and speech recognition. (Sarker, 2021).

2.6 Reviews of Related Works

Machine learning is the process of creating algorithms that allow a computer to learn (Ayodele, 2014). Learning is a process of detecting statistical regularities or other patterns in data, rather than a conscious activity.

In general, the performance of the learning algorithm utilized and the type of data determine the efficacy of any machine learning solution (Sarker, 2021). ML can be classified as supervised, unsupervised, or reinforcement learning.

Gu (2016) in his research work, compared the accuracy and reliability of several different classifiers in recognizing handwriting digits. In his research, he used classifiers such as KNN, Decision Tree, and RFC to carry out a comparative analysis. In his research work, the K-nearest neighbors are the most accurate of the recognizer algorithms (Gu, 2016).

Chumang & Mahasak (2018) suggested a general algorithm for more efficient handwriting recognition in their paper. They used a set of alphabetical photographs in their research, which is a popular method for character identification in this scenario. Bangla, Latin, and MNIST, which are prominent handwritten characters, are the three types of data. The photos used in this experiment are broken down into series. The Bangla Latin MNIST font set was used as the initial set in a test to see how effective this research was. Between the text and the backdrop, the test image is a well-formed typeface. The photo also has a white background. The extraction technique was then used to determine the density of pixels using the principle of extraction (Chumuang & Ketcham, 2018).

Bari, Ambaw & Milos (2019) employed raw digits data that were identified using the SVM, LR (linear regression), DT (Decision Tree), and KNN (K-nearest neighbor). The classifiers are trained on 60,000 photos and evaluated on 10,000 images from the MNIST database of handwritten digits. Any classifier's precision, recall, and F1 score are comparable. The reason for this is that the dataset is evenly distributed. As a result, it promotes the use of accuracy as the appropriate statistic for this issue. The least accurate is DT. The SVM with the RBF (Radial basis function) kernel is the most accurate, followed by the KNN. The former takes more training time, whereas the latter demands more testing time (Bari et al., 2019). As a result, it is one recommended algorithm when the computer power is limited and testing must be completed rapidly.

Baiju & Sabeerath (2016), In their research, used KNN, MLP, and SVM classifiers to test writer independent OHCR (optical handwritten character recognition) for Malayalam script. The main goal of their research is to find the best classifier for a set of features based on recognition accuracy. A database of 44-character classes with 100 samples per class is used to train the algorithm. As features, we use Accurate Dominant Points, Aspect Ratio, Start-End Octants, and Intersections. To reduce training and testing time, the feature vector has been lowered. SVM with RBF kernel had a 95.12% recognition rate, ANN with MLP had a 93.17 percent recognition rate, and KNN had a 90.39 percent recognition rate. And the outcomes are interpreted by the results (Baiju & Sabeerath, 2016).

Premanand, Shubham & Dhruv (2018), in their study, present a feature extraction approach for A hybrid Discrete Wavelet Transform (DWT) and Discrete Cosine Transform is used to recognize handwritten digits and letters (DCT). The obtained features are classified using K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) and Support Vector Machine (SVM) classifiers. The experiment was conducted using the standard MNIST and EMNIST letter datasets. The MNIST digit and EMNIST letter datasets are binary at first, with stray pixels eliminated subsequently. Discrete Wavelet Transform and Discrete Cosine Transform are used to extract features. For classification, KNN and SVM classifiers are utilized. The proposed strategy was successful in obtaining (Ghadekar et al., 2018).

Lavanya, Shaurya, Prateek & Shashwat (2018), proposed a strategy to find an accurate instrument capable of accurately identifying the characters in their investigation. Hundreds of handwritten digit images from the MNIST Dataset are used in the system's training and testing. Before computer processing, data pictures are enhanced by pre-processing. The photos are first transformed to greyscale and then to binary. Following that, the photos are subjected to morphological processes before being converted into comma-separated files for use as Training and Testing Dataset in WEKA. Hoeffding Tree, Decision Tree, and Random Forest techniques are used to recognize patterns, which are then compared against a set of benchmarks (Lavanya et al., 2018).

Vishal and Apurva (2017) offer a system for recognizing online handwritten characters in Gujarati in their research paper. To classify strokes using a hybrid feature set, Support Vector Machines (SVM) with linear, polynomial, and RBF kernels, k-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) with different values of k, and multi-layer perceptron (MLP) are utilized. A collection of 3000 samples was used to train this system, which was then put to the test by 100 distinct writers. The SVM-RBF kernel had the best accuracy of 91.63 percent, while MLP had the lowest accuracy of 86.72 percent (Vishal et al., 2017).

Kumbhar & Kunjir (2017) In their research, they suggested a method for handwriting recognition that uses a machine-learning classification algorithm and may be applied in a variety of industries. The suggested theory intends to acquire images using a camera with high-resolution and apply Image processing algorithms for feature extraction on a single board computer using FPGA-based image processors, OpenCV, or MATLAB. SVM, Backpropagation, and Random Forrest are the machine learning methods chosen for comparison and classification. Precision, recall, efficiency, accuracy, and other quantitative variables are used to compare these algorithms (Kumbhar & Kunjir, 2017).

Norhidayu & Nilam (2017) in their work, to execute classification and read the dataset, proposed an offline handwriting recognition using Python, OpenCV, and Sklearn. They employed the MNIST dataset for classification training and evaluation in their research. MNIST is a dataset used to test machine learning algorithms on the topic of digit classification in handwriting. Several scanned document datasets from the National Institute of Standards and Technology were used to create the dataset (NIST). The images in the collection are all 28 by 28 pixels in size (748 pixels total). The dataset contains 70000 photos that can be used to train and assess the system. Three (3) classification algorithms were used in this suggested system to identify (Hamid & Sjarif, 2017).

Sampath, & Gomathic (2017) in their work, A fuzzy-based spherical SVM classifier was presented for handwritten character recognition. Their main goal was to improve the accuracy of their recognition performance. For feature extraction, the history of oriented gradient (HOG) descriptor is used. The proposed classifier for character recognition is then used to classify the feature. They create a new multi-kernel function based on the fuzzy triangular membership function in the suggested classifier. Finally, the spherical support vector machine is enhanced greatly by using a newly constructed multi-kernel function. Metrics are used to assess and analyse the outcomes and performance of experiments (Sampath & Gomathi, 2017).

Kumar, Jindal, Sharma, & Simpel (2019) in their work, A comparison was carried out on various algorithms such as SVM with RBF, Random forest, KNN, linear SVM on handwritten Gurmukhi characters. Based on their analysis of the test data, it was discovered that the Random forest performs better than the other classifiers with an accuracy of 87.9% for 13,000 samples (Kumar et al., 2019).

Prabha, Ramya, Dinesh, Palanisamy, & Kumar (2020) in their work, carried out a design simulation of a handwritten recognition system. The researchers used classification algorithms such as Logistic Regression, Random Forest, SVM, and KNN for pattern recognition techniques. However, in the comparison to determine the best efficient algorithms, the KNN performs better with an accuracy of 98% (Devi et al., 2020).

Shixiao, Wanyun, & Zhang (2018) in their work, carried out a comparison of handwriting digit recognition using machine learning algorithms such as KNN, SVM, MLP, DT, logistic regress, ANN, and CNN. They achieved this training through MATLAB and anaconda and the results that were achieved show that the SVM with radial basis function achieved a better accuracy of about 98.08% and 97% and lesser running time compared to other estimators. They further improved the accuracy using a graphical processing unit (GPU) with CNN and achieved an accuracy of 99% (Wu et al., 2018).

Bashir, & Ardesir (2018) in their work, carried out a comparative analysis of wavelet neural networks (WNN), ANN, and SVM on offline handwritten recognition. When SVM was compared with ANN, the results shows a reduction of estimation error. However, it is deduced that the ANN can be used to further improve the recognition rate (Saljoughi & Hezarkhani, 2018).

Hu & Ouyang (2019) in their work, combines extreme learning, Random forest, and histogram of oriented gradient (HOG) for feature extraction. The researcher used the MNIST and USPS datasets. The major contribution to this work was to consider the advantage of the HOG and RF. Also, this combines to give a better recognition accuracy of the characters. Finally, this experiment shows that the proposed method achieved a faster training time and recognition accuracy compared to the ML-ELM and HOG-ELM (Ouyang & Hu, 2019).

However, from their papers; (Chumuang & Ketcham, 2018),(Bari et al., 2019), (Baiju & Sabeerath, 2016), (Ghadekar et al., 2018), and (Vishal et al., 2017) that was reviewed in this section shows that SVM was subjected to a comparative analysis with other algorithms. Also, (Lavanya et al., 2018) compared algorithms such as Hoeffding Tree, Decision Tree, and Random Forest techniques tree using a benchmark dataset and WEKA for testing the data. Therefore, the researcher deduced that the SVM with RBF when subjected to a comparative analysis with other classifiers such as decision tree, multi-layer perceptron, and KNN performs better than the other machine learning algorithms.

3.3 Handwritten Text Recognition based on ANN

The researcher has offered an effective technique to the building of a handwritten text recognition system utilizing a 3-layer Artificial Neural Network in this research paper used by (Obaid et al., 2016) in their research. These layers include; pre-processing, segmentation, and feature extraction.

  1. Pre-processing: The image pre-processing stage improves picture sample rendering and prepares the image for segmentation. Pre-major processing's goal is to reduce background noise, enhance the image's region of interest, and produce a clear distinction between background and foreground. We employed noise filtering to do this by transforming our photos to text documents before training the neural network. Our photographs have been converted into text documents, which creates a clear distinction between foreground and background.
  2. Segmentation: In this stage of our work, we decomposed the complete image into a sequence of text. The segmentation is carried out during the testing stage only. It is done based on the detection of the edge and the distance between the different characters. After segmentation, the sub-divided parts are labelled and then processed further. Each sub-image is then resized (12x12) and normalised with itself bringing about 1500 examples of each sign randomly. It helps in the extraction of quality features from images.
  3. Feature Extraction: In this stage, the features are extracted from the character. The feature extraction stage makes it easier for the neural network to be able to classify and identify each character.

3.6 Description of the Proposed System

For detecting and categorizing characters, the suggested system employs an advanced machine learning technique (involving letters and digits). The system uses an android phone camera or webcam to capture the images of the document and then parse the photo into a machine learning algorithm for further analysis. The result of this is a text extracted from the image in a digital format.

The proposed system envisages mitigating the aforementioned problems during manual recognition with three modules which include: pre-processing, feature extraction, and recognition of characters. In the pre-processing module, we will be providing the handwritten documents as scanned images to the computer which will be processed to recognize the characters. The scanning of images can be done using a scanner or a phone camera, but we use a phone camera to scan the image, and then it will be given as input to the system. In the feature extraction module, the recognition rate of the system is depending upon the features of the character. The scanned images of the input file are divided into segments of which each segment contains a character to be recognized, then the feature of each character is extracted with the help of the data stored in the program during the training process of the model. The recognizer module, comes immediately after the feature extraction module, in this module, the system is used to recognize the handwritten characters provided as input to the system. The accuracy of the system was achieved on our system due to the amount of training provided using the three different models on our dataset of which the Random Forest classifier happens to achieve the highest accuracy score on the test data.

The newly proposed system has several advantages as an improvement of the existing system:

  1. Improve the reliability and efficiency of identifying characters from handwritten texts.
  2. Helps these sectors to reduce cost.
  3. It provides real-time identification and recognition of characters.
  4. The system mitigates the challenges faced by banks, postal services, schools among others to increase efficiency and productivity among employees.
  5. The system helps to improve the accuracy in identifying and recognizing the characters without delay.

3.6.1 Dataset for the Proposed System

The NIST's complete number of training resources for hand-printed documents and recognition of character is housed in NIST special dataset 19. NIST special datasets 3 and 7 are superseded by this dataset. It publishes hand-printed samples of 810,000-character images separated from their forms, ground truth classifications for those images, reference forms for additional data gathering, and software tools for image management and handling were created from 3600 writers. The database has the following features:

  1. NIST's hand-printed sample data has been compiled in its final form.
  2. Page in its entirety 3600 writers submitted HSF (strong sarcastic font) forms.
  3. Separate digits, and text fields in both upper and lower case with no restrictions
  4. There are almost 800,000 photos with categories that have been checked by hand.

The dataset is the largest and final release of pictures designed for handprint document processing and OCR research from the National Institute of Standards and Technology. An example image of the dataset from NIST DB 19 is shown in Figure 3.3.

Figure 3.3 Sample images of NIST database 19 (Cheng-Lin Liu. et al., 2004)

3.6.2 Data Pre-processing and Training

Generally, in machine learning pre-processing of data is said to be the changes made to our data before it is fed to the model. This indicates that pre-processing of data is a method for transforming the raw data into a clean dataset. To put it another way, whenever data is acquired from several sources. The data are collected in a raw format, which makes analysis impossible. Data pre-processing is important to improve the results of machine learning projects using the applicable model. A particular ML model requires data in a specific format. Because the RFC classification algorithm does not tolerate null values, null values must be managed from the original raw dataset to run the algorithm. Hence the dataset should be designed such that many machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be run simultaneously using a single dataset, and the most accurate in terms of recognition will be selected among them. In our work, we carried out pre-processing and resizing of the images by converting the images into text documents. For this research, the researcher trained our custom dataset using SVM, KNN, and Random forest machine learning classification algorithms.

3.8.1.1 Anaconda Environment

Anaconda Environment is an open-source distribution of Python and R data science packages. Anaconda environment supports multiple versions of python and associated packages. Data science, statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning are all done in this environment. The conda package framework handles consumer designs.

3.8.1.2 Scikit-Learn Python

Scikit-Learn (Sklearn) is a Python-based library in ML that one can obtain for free. It supports python numerical and scientific libraries including NumPy and SciPy, as well as machine learning methods like support vector machine, random forests, K-nearest neighbor, and decision tree.

3.8.1.3 Flask

Flask is a python-based microweb framework. Flask is a Python web framework that provides libraries, modules, and tools to aid in the development of web applications. The jinja template engine and the Werkzeug WSGI toolkit are required by Flask.

3.8.1.4 PyTesseract

PyTesseract, sometimes known as python-tesseract, is a Python utility for optical character recognition. It will recognize and read the text hidden in photographs, in other words.

Tesseract-OCR Engine by Google is wrapped in Python-tesseract. All image type is supported by Pillow and Leptonica imaging library, including png, jpeg, gif, BMP, tiff, and others, making it handy as a standalone tesseract invocation script. Tesseract will also display the recognized text rather than writing it to a file if used as a script.

3.8.1.5 Pillow

Pillow is a python-imaging module that extends image processing capabilities of the python interpreter. Wide range of file formats can be read and written by this library. The core image library is also designed to give easy access to data saved in few sample pixel formats.

4.5 System Testing

System testing entails a qualitative assessment of the new system in light of the user requirements gathered and the system specifications. This procedure assures that the system is error-free, generates the intended outcomes, and operates in a highly secure, efficient, and dependable manner. This procedure includes validating and verifying the system to ensure that it fits the requirements. Component/unit testing, integration testing, system testing, and acceptance testing are the four (4) levels of testing.

  • Unit Testing: Individual units or functions of software are tested separately with varied parameters as part of unit testing to guarantee the system is error-free.
  • Integration Testing: Integration testing, often known as integration and IT testing is a type of testing that looks at how different components interact and how subsystems work together to form a single system and overall compliance with the requirements. Consider viewing the signup and login pages separately.
  • System Testing: System testing is carried out on a fully integrated system to see whether it complies with the specified requirements.
  • Acceptance Testing: Acceptance testing is a sort of software testing that determines whether or not a system is acceptable. The primary purpose of this test is to see if the system meets the business requirements and is ready to go.

CHAPTER FIVE

SUMMARY, RECOMMENDATION, AND CONCLUSION

5.1 Summary

The processes involved in object detection of handwriting recognition involve so many processes of high-level classification accuracy and time complexities that may result from the processes. Character recognition is the main module of the application of the handwriting recognition system. The image of letters and digits to be recognized plays a vital role in the classification problem. Through identifying the letters has helped so many sectors such as banks, postal services, and schools carry out handwritten text recognition operations effectively. The availability of large volumes of data, packages, and graphical processing units (GPUs) hardware has made the researcher extract features from data using neural networks.

However, various existing systems built by the previous researcher as reviewed in the literature section tend to solve some problems associated with the existing system but not completely. Some carried out comparative analysis on different machine learning algorithms on handwritten data but were not able to build an application that can be used in the various sectors.

Therefore, the existing system is faced with various drawbacks ranging from functionality to the performance of the system such as:

  1. Accuracy in identifying characters
  2. The time is taken to identify characters
  3. The existing system does not support character recognition.

Thus, manually detecting and identifying the handwritten texts thereby leading to time consumption and lower production of employees. This research retrains the use of pytesseract to efficiently scanned through images and extract texts written on the images.

5.1.1 Justification of the new system

The evaluation processes of the current system start with a proper examination of the existing system. The evaluations show that the process of recognizing handwritten characters can be tedious, inefficient, unreliable due to the presence of human errors; and also, can be stressful and reduced productivity among employees of various sectors such as banks, postal services, schools. Hence, the process of recognizing handwritten characters using a computer system can be computationally tasking. As a result of this experts in the various sectors use only eyes to recognize handwritten characters.

However, several improvements have to be made in the new system to reduce the complexity, inefficiency, cost and computational time, reliability, and performance of the new system. The new system will use a phone camera to capture an image from text documents or handwritten characters, and then the image will be uploaded to the flask application which will be processed to extract texts from the image.

The system will help increase productivity among employees, and also helps companies to save costs in paying experts who carry out this task manually. In addition, the system implements a model on a web server using a flask web framework.

5.1.2 Review of achievements

On carrying this research work, the researcher was able to:

  1. Pre-process an existing dataset relevant for this study.
  2. Train and test the SVM, KNN, and RFC machine learning models.
  3. Carry out a comparative analysis on SVM, KNN, and RFC machine learning models.
  4. Capture different test images using a phone camera.
  5. Deploy the machine learning model that has performed better on the test data to the Flask web framework.
  6. Achieved a high recognition accuracy.

5.2 Conclusion

Optical character recognition of character from the images is an important research area in the field of pattern recognition, image processing and machine learning many things are yet to be discovered and many new algorithms are to be developed (R. Singh, 2017). Many frameworks are already developed to detect handwritten characters and classify them, but when it comes to a real-world scenario, the issue arises in the implementation. In the Random Forest model, we achieved a 100% accuracy score, but there are some limitations which are faced by our research as well; the RFC model upon deployment can recognize all characters from captured text documents but could not recognize all characters from handwritten texts. Hence, these issues are to be addressed by future works. We can also improve the scanning speed.

However, at the end of this research work, the researcher successfully deployed our random forest classifier model and developed a web application for character recognition. The researcher employed pytesseract to the deployed web application for the recognition of characters.

5.3 Recommendations

The pytesseract OCR is highly recommended for integration on optical character recognition systems. The research goes further to create a web app for handwriting recognition which is recommended for banks, postal services, schools, and OCR can also be used by airports to automate the process of passport recognition and data extraction. Other applications of OCR include data entry automation and the detection and recognition of vehicle license plates.

5.4 Suggestion for Further Work

Considering the achievements and limitations of the research, the researcher intends to keep making improvements to the recognition accuracy of the handwriting model by expanding the datasets and collecting the data ourselves to get cleaner data. Also, we intend to make the system recognize characters from other languages such as Arabic. In this research, the researcher has developed a web app interface to demonstrate handwriting using a phone camera. The researcher was not able to make the scanning process faster due to limited computing resources. In the future, the researcher may make the browser allow a user to tap into a machine's camera and record photographs with their consent, which can be quite useful, particularly on mobile devices. If the researcher adds camera capabilities, the user does not have to capture the image and then upload it to the website; instead, the user acts directly through the mobile application. This will speed up the scanning process.

Ocr_pro.py

try:

    from PIL import Image

except ImportError:

    import Image

import pytesseract

def ocr_core(filename):

    """

    This function will handle the core OCR processing of images.

    """

    text = pytesseract.image_to_string(Image.open(filename))  # We'll use Pillow's Image class to open the image and pytesseract to detect the string in the image

    return text

print(ocr_core('images/image.png'))

app.py

import os

from flask import Flask,render_template,redirect,url_for,request

#import our OCR function

from ocr_pro import ocr_core

#define a folder to store and later serve the images

UPLOAD_FOLDER = '/static/Test_Images/'

#allow files of a specific type

ALLOWED_EXTENSIONS = set(['png','jpg','jpeg','gif','tiff','tif'])

app = Flask(__name__)

#app.config['DEBUG']=True

# function to check the file extension

def allowed_file(filename):

    return '.' in filename and \

            filename.rsplit('.', 1)[1].lower() in ALLOWED_EXTENSIONS

            

# route and function to handle the home page

@app.route("/", methods=['GET', 'POST'])

def login():

    if request.method == 'POST':

        return redirect(url_for('upload'))

        userEmail = request.form['username']

        userPassword = request.form['password']

        return flask.redirect('/')

        

    return render_template("login.html" )

    

@app.route("/signup", methods=['GET', 'POST'])

def signup():

    if request.method == 'POST':

        return redirect(url_for('login'))

    return render_template("signup.html")

    

    

@app.route("/upload", methods=['GET','POST'])

def upload():

    if request.method == 'POST':

        #check if there is a file in the request

        if 'file' not in request.files:

            return render_template('upload.html', msg='No file selected')

        file = request.files['file']

        # if no file is selected

        if file.filename == '':

            return render_template('upload.html', msg='No file selected')

        if file and allowed_file(file.filename):

            

            # call the OCR function on it

            extracted_text = ocr_core(file)

            

            # extract the text and display it

            return render_template('upload.html', msg='Successfully processed', extracted_text=extracted_text,img_src=UPLOAD_FOLDER + file.filename)

    elif request.method == 'GET':

        return render_template('upload.html')

        

if __name__ == "__main__":

    app.run(debug=True)
